<subSubSection lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="615" pageId="19" pageNumber="614" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="19.[1427,2633,3333,3485]" pageId="19" pageNumber="614">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nehring" authorityYear="1891" box="[1430,1625,3367,3400]" class="Mammalia" family="Talpidae" genus="Mogera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="19" pageNumber="614" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="robusta">Mogera robusta</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[1697,1837,3367,3400]" class="Mammalia" family="Talpidae" genus="Mogera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="19" pageNumber="615" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="wogura">M. wogura</taxonomicName>
were considered the same species, but mtDNA data suggested their distinctiveness. Nuclear DNA data indicated more complex pattern with clusters involving both M. robustaand 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[1956,2095,3445,3478]" class="Mammalia" family="Talpidae" genus="Mogera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="19" pageNumber="615" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="wogura">M. wogura</taxonomicName>
. Moles occupying southern part of the
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[750,1341,295,722]" pageId="20" pageNumber="615">
Korean Peninsula have often been considered a valid species or a subspecies coreana, related either to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nehring" authorityYear="1891" box="[996,1137,374,407]" class="Mammalia" family="Talpidae" genus="Mogera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="20" pageNumber="615" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="robusta">M. robusta</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Temminck" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[1191,1335,374,407]" class="Mammalia" family="Talpidae" genus="Mogera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Soricomorpha" pageId="20" pageNumber="615" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="wogura">M. wogura</taxonomicName>
. True phylogenetic relationships are still uncertain. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="615" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6678207" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6678207" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6678207/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="615" targetBox="[135,726,303,709]" targetPageId="20">
<paragraph blockId="20.[750,1341,295,722]" pageId="20" pageNumber="615">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[750,926,492,525]" pageId="20" pageNumber="615">Distribution.</emphasis>
NE China (Inner Mongolia [= Nei Mongol], Heilongjiang, Jilin, and Liaoning), SE Russian Far East, and Korean Peninsula.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="615" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="20.[750,1341,295,722]" lastBlockId="20.[135,1341,729,1550]" pageId="20" pageNumber="615">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[750,1030,649,682]" pageId="20" pageNumber="615">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 147-165 mm, tail 1620-5 mm, hindfoot 18-21 mm; weight 95-9-127-3 g. Tail is 0-3-13-4% head-body length. The Ussuri Mole is large; dorsum is brownish, mixed with gray metallic sheen, and venter has shiny silvery yellow hue. Skull is stout, and rostrum is broad. Dental formulais 13/2, C 1/1, P 4/4, M 3/3 (x2) = 42. Extensive dental abnormalities were found specimens from Primorskii Krai, Russia. Chromosomal complement has 2n = 36 and FNa = 58 from Korea.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="615" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="20.[135,1341,729,1550]" pageId="20" pageNumber="615">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[137,248,934,959]" pageId="20" pageNumber="615">Habitat.</emphasis>
Montane woodland, forests, grasslands, and farmlands. The Ussuri Mole is rarely found on steep slopes with rocky soils. In Russia, it is absent from elevations above 500-700 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="615" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="20.[135,1341,729,1550]" pageId="20" pageNumber="615">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[137,398,1052,1077]" pageId="20" pageNumber="615">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
The Ussuri Mole eats insects, their larvae, earthworms, millipedes, and centipedes. Mollusks, spiders, and mice are rarely eaten.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="615" type="breeding">
<paragraph blockId="20.[135,1341,729,1550]" pageId="20" pageNumber="615">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[137,271,1122,1155]" pageId="20" pageNumber="615">Breeding.</emphasis>
Breeding of the Ussuri Mole occurs from late March to mid-August. There are two litters annually at the end of May and in July; litters have 2-10 young (mean 6-9). Young nurse for 26-30 days and attain sexual maturity at 10-11 months old.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="615" type="activity">
<paragraph blockId="20.[135,1341,729,1550]" pageId="20" pageNumber="615">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[135,375,1240,1273]" pageId="20" pageNumber="615">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
The Ussuri Mole is fossorial and excavates molehills 20-45 cm in diameter and 10-25 cm high.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="615" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="20.[135,1341,729,1550]" pageId="20" pageNumber="615">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[137,855,1319,1352]" pageId="20" pageNumber="615">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
Densities of Ussuri Moles are up 2-5 ind/ha.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[137,1187,1398,1431]" pageId="20" pageNumber="615" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="20.[135,1341,729,1550]" box="[137,1187,1398,1431]" pageId="20" pageNumber="615">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[137,486,1398,1431]" pageId="20" pageNumber="615">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Least Concern on The IUCN Red List.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
